      "content": "thanks for the breakdown. but u said the originalist stuff is \"principled\" and \"internally consistent\" while the other side's critique is just that it's \"problematic\" for modern use. doesn't that kind of imply that originalism is a legit legal philosophy while the other side is just complaining about the results? \n\nlike, if the originalist method is logically sound and follows the text, isn't it more of a \"real\" legal theory than just a way to say \"we don't like this\"? isn't the \"living constitution\" idea just a way to bypass the actual law when it doesn't fit modern politics?",
